full_text: In some circumstances, a legal matter becomes a hearing before an administrative law judge, or ALJ. The ALJ role must be added to ClaimCenter, and to matters. There can only be one ALJ for a given matter. I begin by adding the role to the Contact Role Type List, which specifies the possible roles for a contact. I add a new type code. I give it a short code, using the suffix underscore SI, for succeed insurance. Both the name and description properties will be Administrative Law Judge. I add a new type code. The contact role category type list categorizes contact types for filtering purposes. Administrative Law Judge should be categorized under litigation. The litigation type code is already selected, so I click Next. The Contact Role Category Type List is selected, but I need the Contact Role Type List, so I click the up key. In the Category List, I select ALJ underscore SI. And click Finish. Entity role constraints define what kind of contacts can have what kind of roles. To configure entity role constraints for the ALJ, I navigate to the Entity role constraints config.xml file. I type left bracket, C and select Contact Role Type Constraint. When I select Contact Role Type Cone Tron, two properties appear. For the Contact Role Code property, I enter ALJ underscore SI. And for the Contact Subtype property, I enter Adjudicator, remembering to close the tag with a backslash. Now I have to add the code to the Matter entity, so I scroll down to find it. Again, I will preserve alphabetical order by placing the ALJ at the top. I add a new Role Ref tag, using ALJ underscore SI as the code. Now I type left bracket R and select Role Constraint. For the Constraint Type, I enter Exclusive, indicating that only one contact may have this role. I end the tag with a backslash. To test my work, I start the Claim Center server in debug mode. When the server is started, I log into Claim Center as Andy Applegate. I navigate to a claim. And on its litigation page, I see that there is an existing matter. Now I navigate to the contacts list. I will create a new contact as an adjudicator. I want to assign a new contact the role of Administrative Law Judge. But I can't. The Administrative Law Judge role does not appear on this list. This is because I am trying to relate it to the claim, and the ALJ role can only be related to a matter. If I change the Related to field so that the role will be related to the matter. The Administrative Law Judge role is available. I select it. I fill in the one required field, the last name. And click Update. Now I'll try adding another ALJ. Once again, I will give the new contact the Administrative Law Judge role, related to the matter. A last name is required. Now, when I click Update. An error message indicates that there can only be one ALJ associated with a given matter. This is because of the exclusive constraint I placed on ALJ. I will be able to add a new contact. So I'll just cancel the new contact. This concludes the Adding a Claim Contact role demonstration. segments.text: In some circumstances, a legal matter becomes a hearing before an administrative law judge, or ALJ. The ALJ role must be added to ClaimCenter, and to matters. There can only be one ALJ for a given matter. I begin by adding the role to the Contact Role Type List, which specifies the possible roles for a contact.
I add a new type code. I give it a short code, using the suffix underscore SI, for succeed insurance. Both the name and description properties will be Administrative Law Judge.
I add a new type code. The contact role category type list categorizes contact types for filtering purposes. Administrative Law Judge should be categorized under litigation.
The litigation type code is already selected, so I click Next.
The Contact Role Category Type List is selected, but I need the Contact Role Type List, so I click the up key. In the Category List, I select ALJ underscore SI.
And click Finish.
Entity role constraints define what kind of contacts can have what kind of roles.
To configure entity role constraints for the ALJ, I navigate to the Entity role constraints config.xml file.
I type left bracket, C and select Contact Role Type Constraint.
When I select Contact Role Type Cone Tron, two properties appear.
For the Contact Role Code property, I enter ALJ underscore SI.
And for the Contact Subtype property, I enter Adjudicator, remembering to close the tag with a backslash.
Now I have to add the code to the Matter entity, so I scroll down to find it.
Again, I will preserve alphabetical order by placing the ALJ at the top.
I add a new Role Ref tag, using ALJ underscore SI as the code.
Now I type left bracket R and select Role Constraint.
For the Constraint Type, I enter Exclusive, indicating that only one contact may have this role.
I end the tag with a backslash.
To test my work, I start the Claim Center server in debug mode.
When the server is started, I log into Claim Center as Andy Applegate.
I navigate to a claim.
And on its litigation page, I see that there is an existing matter.
Now I navigate to the contacts list.
I will create a new contact as an adjudicator.
I want to assign a new contact the role of Administrative Law Judge.
But I can't.
The Administrative Law Judge role does not appear on this list.
This is because I am trying to relate it to the claim, and the ALJ role can only be related to a matter.
If I change the Related to field so that the role will be related to the matter.
The Administrative Law Judge role is available.
I select it.
I fill in the one required field, the last name.
And click Update.
Now I'll try adding another ALJ.
Once again, I will give the new contact the Administrative Law Judge role, related to the matter.
A last name is required.
Now, when I click Update.
An error message indicates that there can only be one ALJ associated with a given matter.
This is because of the exclusive constraint I placed on ALJ.
I will be able to add a new contact.
So I'll just cancel the new contact.
This concludes the Adding a Claim Contact role demonstration.
